data.chText: 开始发生；开始；着手
data.enText: to begin to happen; to begin sth

data.chText: 会议定于午间召开。
data.enText: The meeting is scheduled to commence at noon.

data.chText: 那天由校长致欢迎词开始。
data.enText: The day commenced with a welcome from the principal.

data.chText: 我将从2月15日开始一周的休假。
data.enText: I will be on leave during the week commencing 15 February.

data.chText: 她于1956年开始行医。
data.enText: She commenced her medical career in 1956.

data.chText: 我们下周破土动工。
data.enText: We commence building next week.

data.text: start ♦ begin ♦ start off ♦ kick off ♦ commence ♦ open ♦ get under way

data.chText: 以上各词均用以指事情开始发生或开始做某事。
data.enText: These words are all used to talk about things happening from the beginning, or people doing the first part of sth.
start

data.chText: 指开始发生或存在、以…开始、以…为起点：
data.enText: to begin to happen or exist; to begin in a particular way or from a particular point

data.chText: 什么时候上课？
data.enText: When does the class start?
begin

data.chText: 指开始发生或存在、以…开始、以…为起点、开始讲话：
data.enText: to start to happen or exist; to start in a particular way or from a particular point; to start speaking

data.chText: 音乐会什么时候开始？
data.enText: When does the concert begin?

data.chText: 用start还是begin？
上述两词在意义上无多大差别，start较常用于英语口语和商业语境中，begin较常用于英语书面语中，描述一系列事情：
data.enText: There is not much difference in meaning between these words. Start is more frequent in spoken English and in business contexts; begin is more frequent in written English and is often used when you are describing a series of events.

data.chText: 故事从科孚岛开始。
data.enText: The story begins on the island of Corfu.

data.chText: start不用以指开始讲话：
data.enText: Start is not used to mean ‘begin speaking’.
‘Ladies and gentlemen,’ he started.
start or begin?
start off

data.chText: 指进行或开展起来、首先进行、一开始是：
data.enText: ( rather informal ) to start happening or doing sth; to start by doing or being sth

data.chText: 讨论颇为温和地开展起来。
data.enText: The discussion started off mildly enough.
kick off

data.chText: 尤指以…开始（活动）、（活动）以…开始：
data.enText: ( informal ) to start an event or activity, especially in a particular way; (of an event, activity, etc.) to start, especially in a particular way

data.chText: 汤姆讲话时要先发表几点意见。
data.enText: Tom will kick off with a few comments.

data.chText: 节期从9月13日星期一开始。
data.enText: The festival kicks off on Monday, September 13.
commence

data.chText: 指开始发生：
data.enText: ( formal ) to start happening

data.chText: 会议定于午间召开。
data.enText: The meeting is scheduled to commence at noon.
open

data.chText: 指以…开始（活动）、（活动、电影或书）以…开头／开篇：
data.enText: to start an event or activity in a particular way; (of an event, film/movie or book) to start, especially in a particular way

data.chText: 故事以一宗谋杀案作序幕。
data.enText: The story opens with a murder.
get under way

data.chText: 指开始：
data.enText: to start

data.chText: 五月份特别活动周的准备工作已经开始。
data.enText: Preparations have got under way for a week of special events in May.

data.chText: get under way最常与season、preparations、discussions、day和investigation 等词连用。
data.enText: Get under way is used most often with such words as season , preparations , discussions , day , and investigation .
to start/begin/start off/kick off/commence/open/get under way with sth
to start/begin/start off/kick off/commence/open/get under way by doing sth
to start/begin/start off/commence as sth
a campaign/season/meeting starts/begins/starts off/kicks off/commences/opens/gets under way
a film/movie/book starts/begins/starts off/opens
to start/begin all over again
Let's start/begin/start off/kick off/commence/open/get under way (with sth)

ex.chText: 这艘游艇将于下周开始它的处女航。
ex.enText: The yacht will start its maiden voyage next week.

ex.chText: 把泥弄湿点再动手塑形。
ex.enText: Wet the clay a bit more before you start to mould it.

synonyms.bx: 指动作开始且持续下去，强调开始这一事实。

ex.chText: 这节课是从一个故事开始的。
ex.enText: The class began/started with a story.

ex.chText: 你何时开始学习日语的？
ex.enText: When did you begin/start learning Japanese?

synonyms.bx: 最常用词，指为某一过程或进程开个头，常可与 start 换用。

ex.enText: When will the opening ceremony commence?

ex.chText: 服务业的进一步谈判将于2012年开启。
ex.enText: Further negotiations on services will commence in 2012.

synonyms.bx: 指开始某种正式行动，常伴有正式程序或一定的仪式，语气庄重。

tips.tip: 以上这组词作为瞬时动词，通常不可与表示一段时间的状语连用。

tr: take the first step or steps in carrying out an action
example: Get working as soon as the sun rises!
The first tourists began to arrive in Cambodia
He began early in the day
Let's get down to work now

tr: set in motion, cause to start
example: The U.S. started a war in the Middle East
begin a new chapter in your life
We embarked on an exciting enterprise
I start my day with a good breakfast
The afternoon session begins at 4 PM
The blood shed started when the partisans launched a surprise attack

value.def: When something commences or you commence it, it begins.

example.ex: The academic year commences at the beginning of October...

example.tran: 他们开始进行彻底搜查。

example.ex: The hunter knelt beside the animal carcass and commenced to skin it.
example.tran: 猎人跪在动物尸体旁边，开始剥皮。

value.boxu_tran: commence, start 和 begin 三个词意思相近，不过 commence 一词更为正式，通常不用于对话中。例如，The meeting is ready to begin (会议可以开始了)，He tore the list up and started a fresh one (他把清单撕碎，然后另列一张)，an alternative to commencing the process of European integration (启动欧洲一体化进程的另一种方式)。注意 begin, start 和 commence 都能后接动词的 -ing 形式或名词，但只有 begin 和 start 才能后接不定式。
value.boxu_usage: Commence, start, and begin all have a similar meaning, although commence is more formal and is not normally used in conversation. The meeting is ready to begin... He tore the list up and started a fresh one. ...an alternative to commencing the process of European integration. Note that begin, start, and commence can all be followed by an -ing form or a noun, but only begin and start can be followed by a 'to' infinitive.
